text.tspan: Hello. I'm Hannah, and I'm here to help you
learn how to use some basic git commands.
I'm going to assume that if you here, then you
either have no experience with using git or have
only used git via an IDE.
I will cover all you need to know to work with an
existing repository and to save changes back to it.
Here we won't cover how to create your own
repository or the more advanced features of git.
Although git is very powerful, I want to help you
get started as soon as possible. You can read my
other guides on the more advanced features or do
your own research once you know the basics.
What is git?
Git is a powerful version control system used by many
projects to maintain their code base and help manage
changes.
One important aspect of git is that it is an example
of a distributed version control system. You will see
why this is relevant later, but for now you just need to
know this means that every user of a repository gets
their own copy of the full version history of that
repository.
There are many git repository hosts available, some
you may have heard of are gitlab, github and
bitbucket. You can even host a git repository yourself
if you wish, although we won't be covering that today.
